Class CrossPanel

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.awt.Component
      • java.awt.Container

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.awt.image.ImageObserver, java.awt.MenuContainer, java.io.Serializable, javax.accessibility.Accessible

    public class CrossPanel
extends javax.swing.JPanel
    This class was originally developed so that Capabilities could be associated with computers - that is what was available on the computer. Similarly to associate the Capabilities needed by Jobs. There is a Capabilities, Jobs and Computer table and the cross or relation table which would have Job.id and Capability.id in it as well as an amount of the capability required.

    requirements : This class represents a class entirely made up of ids from two other related classes. The classes are Cross1 and Cross2 and their primary values must be cross1 and cross2 (like most simple tables within the GUI. The GUI creates a JCOmboBox of the two keys values and two more JComboBoxes for the settings of the two values for this particular one.

    The reports pane is to give feedback to the user about the relation. Originally it would do something like show the first 1000 of the relation as an example. If the Cross1 is selected then it would show all relations involving that key so the entire scope is shown.

    If the user tries to to pick a Cross1 and Cross2 that already exist in the relation, that relation is just displayed even though when the user Selected Cross1 the screen might show a new relation is to be defined.

    TO change this for crossed tables A and B:

    1) Change "Cross1" to A, "cross1" to "a", "Cross2" to B and "cross2" to "b"

    2) In Form mode change JComboBox variables name "cross1" to "a" and "cross2" to "b"

    3) If the report field is to be used, in doOldOne write a correct SQL Statement for the report.

    The use can edit the JCombos, but this really just creates a new relation between the two tables.
